      "description": "By the spring 1994 Awake sessions, Mike Portnoy had refined and expanded the Tama setup he had used on Images and Words. The core kit remained Tama Artstar II / Granstar birch — Tama's flagship professional shells of the early-to-mid 90s — but the configuration grew to match the more architecturally demanding music. The expanded tom range, with 8\", 10\", 12\", 14\", and 16\" sizes, gave Portnoy nearly two full octaves of melodic vocabulary and let him construct the wide-arc fills that defined tracks like \"6:00\" and \"Erotomania.\"\n\nThe double 22\" bass drum configuration carried over from Images and Words, but the playing approach evolved. Where the 1992 album used double bass as syncopation and accent, the Awake sessions deployed it as sustained low-end pressure — the relentless eighth-note pulse under \"The Mirror,\" the driving sixteenth patterns in the \"A Mind Beside Itself\" suite, and the punishing footwork in \"Lifting Shadows Off a Dream\" all required a kit that could deliver weight as well as articulation. The birch shells of the Artstar II/Granstar handled this well: birch's pronounced low end and crisp high attack let the bass drums punch through Devonshire's dense ambient capture without losing definition.\n\nThe toms themselves were tuned slightly lower than on Images and Words, matching the heavier overall tonal palette. The 8\" and 10\" rack toms still spoke with the bright crack Portnoy preferred for fast melodic passages, but the 12\" and 14\" rack toms and 16\" floor tom were tensioned to give up more body and sustain — useful for the more cinematic fill writing across \"Scarred\" and \"Space-Dye Vest.\"\n\nThe Star-Cast mounting system — Tama's then-recent innovation that suspended each tom from its lugs rather than drilling through the shell — preserved shell resonance and was crucial for the longer sustain Portnoy needed in this era. Visually, the black lacquer finish replaced the Images and Words purple, signaling the darker thematic identity of the new record.",
