      "size": "14\" x 6.5\"",
      "shell": "Bell Brass",
      "description": "The single most important sonic upgrade Mike Portnoy made for Awake was the snare drum. He moved from the Artstar II brass snare he had used on Images and Words to the legendary Tama Bell Brass — a heavy, dense brass shell prized in the 80s and 90s for its combination of cracking attack, fat body, and almost gong-like sustain. The Bell Brass was the same shell formula behind some of the most celebrated rock snare sounds of the era, and on Awake it gave Portnoy a snare voice that could anchor both whisper-quiet passages and full-throated double-bass attacks.\n\nAt 14\" x 6.5\", the Bell Brass had the depth to project under heavy guitars and the sensitivity to articulate the rapid ghost-note work that runs through \"6:00,\" \"Caught in a Web,\" and \"Voices.\" The snare's tonal weight is one of the first things that distinguishes Awake's sound from Images and Words — the crack is fatter, the sustain is denser, and the drum sits lower in the spectrum without sacrificing definition.\n\nCo-producers John Purdell and Duane Baron captured the snare with both a top microphone for attack and a bottom microphone for snare-wire response, then compressed and EQ'd the result heavily to match the album's denser overall mix. This is a more processed snare sound than David Prater achieved on Images and Words, but the processing serves the music — Awake's darker emotional palette demanded a snare with more presence and weight.\n\nPortnoy tuned the Bell Brass in the medium range for this recording, slightly looser than his Images and Words approach. The looser tuning gave the drum more body and resonance, supporting the longer melodic phrases that recur across the album.",
