      "description": "Mike Portnoy was a Sabian endorser throughout the 1990s, and the Awake sessions document the deepest version of his Sabian setup before the eventual move toward the Artisan series later in the decade. The 1994 rig combined the brighter, more cutting AA series (Sabian's automated-hammered cymbals) with the darker, hand-hammered HH series for tonal variety across the album's wide emotional range.\n\nThe 14\" AA Rock Hi-Hats were heavier than the standard AA pair, giving Portnoy the weight to chop through Devonshire's denser mix without losing articulation. Listen to the opening of \"6:00\" — those hi-hats cut through everything around them, even as the guitars stack into a wall of low end.\n\nThe HH 17\" Medium-Thin Crash and the HH 19\" Crash provided the darker, more musical accent voices on the kit. Hand-hammered cymbals produce a more complex overtone structure than machine-hammered models, and Portnoy used these for the more emotionally weighted moments — the climactic crashes in \"Space-Dye Vest,\" the layered accents across \"Scarred,\" and the transition moments in \"The Mirror.\"\n\nThe AA 16\" and 18\" crashes filled the brighter accent roles — quick, cutting hits for tempo changes and fill endpoints. The variety between AA and HH gave Portnoy a palette where every crash had a slightly different tonal character, which served the through-composed sectional writing of tracks like \"A Mind Beside Itself.\"\n\nThe HH 22\" Raw Bell Dry Ride is one of the signature cymbal choices of the Awake era. Dark, dry, and articulate, with a raw unlathed bell that cuts through any density, this ride became closely associated with Portnoy's mid-90s sound. It rides cleanly through \"Lifting Shadows Off a Dream\" and provides the bell accents that punctuate \"Caught in a Web.\"\n\nThe AA 18\" Chinese added trashy aggression — essential for the heaviest passages, where Portnoy uses it as a punctuation mark on top of the bass drum hits.",
