      "size": "14\" x 6.5\"",
      "shell": "Maple",
      "description": "The Starclassic Maple snare that had served the *Scenes from a Memory* sessions continued into the *Six Degrees* recording, matched tonally to the kit and calibrated for the album's dynamic range. At 6.5\" depth, it provided the body to cut through dense arrangements while retaining the sensitivity needed for the ghost-note work that defines the title suite's quieter movements.\n\nThe snare on \"The Glass Prison\" is tuned for authority — driving the track's powerful, confessional intensity with each backbeat carrying personal weight. But the same drum, in the hands of a drummer thinking narratively, adapts throughout the double album. The ghost notes that appear in softer passages of the title suite require a snare that speaks at low velocities without forcing the player to overcompensate.\n\nEngineer sound was captured at BearTracks with the same close-mic approach that had served SFaM well — batter head top mic for attack, resonant head mic for wire sensitivity, blended to create a presence that sits in the midfield of the mix. For a 100-minute double album, midfield snare placement was essential — too prominent and it fatigues across two discs, too recessed and the rhythmic backbone of songs like \"The Great Debate\" loses definition.\n\nTuned in the medium-to-medium-high range, the snare balanced the warmth the maple concept demanded with enough tension to deliver decisive attacks on the album's most aggressive passages.",
