      "description": "For the *Six Degrees* sessions, Mike Portnoy maintained the Sabian Artisan and HH series configuration that had defined the *Scenes from a Memory* era. The Artisan line's dark, hand-hammered character was still the right sonic palette for music with the emotional complexity of a concept double album — brighter cymbals would have fought against the title suite's more introspective movements.\n\nThe 14\" Artisan hi-hats delivered the warm articulation that the title suite required. In movements like \"About to Crash (Reprise)\" and \"Solitary Shell,\" Portnoy's hi-hat technique is as compositional as his tom work — half-open hi-hats creating texture rather than simply marking time, tight closed patterns providing pulse without aggression. The Artisan's complex, layered voice made this expressive variety possible in a way that brighter cymbals wouldn't have permitted.\n\nFor \"The Glass Prison\" and the Disc 1 heavy tracks, the same Artisan cymbals proved adaptable. The crashes respond differently at high-velocity impacts — opening up more, sustaining longer — and Portnoy used this characteristic to mark the emotional peaks of the personal material with crashes that bloom rather than cut.\n\nThe Artisan 20\" ride remained central to the quiet passages. Its warm bell tone — used extensively across the title suite's gentler sections — provided the shimmering, sustained quality that served as sonic punctuation between characters and movements. The bell is never aggressive on this album; it functions as a musical element rather than a rhythmic tool.\n\nThe HH Chinese added aggressive punctuation capability without requiring a full cymbal change — a critical resource for an album that moves between heavy and quiet within single tracks, sometimes within single minutes.",
