      "description": "For *Black Clouds & Silver Linings*, Mike Portnoy continued with the Tama Starclassic **Bubinga** kit that had defined his sound on *Systematic Chaos* (2007). Having made the transition from Maple to Bubinga in the mid-decade and spent two years touring the expanded configuration extensively, Portnoy arrived at the *Black Clouds* sessions with a drum kit he knew completely.\n\nBubinga's sonic character — sharper attack, tighter decay, and more articulate transients compared to Maple — remained the right choice for an album that again demanded extraordinary range. \"A Rite of Passage\" required the same relentless attack that \"Constant Motion\" and \"The Dark Eternal Night\" had demanded on *Systematic Chaos*. \"The Count of Tuscany\" required the bubinga's clarity to keep individual drum voices distinct across 19 minutes of evolving musical architecture. And \"The Best of Times\" required the shells to respond with precision and restraint across one of the most emotionally charged performances of Portnoy's career.\n\nThe configuration maintained the large ~13-drum layout that had been Portnoy's standard since *Train of Thought*: double 22\"x18\" bass drums, five rack toms (8\" through 14\"), and three floor toms (14\", 16\", 18\"). Tama's Star-Cast mounting system preserved the bubinga shells' resonance across all positions. Every drum in the configuration had a clear musical purpose across the album's five main tracks.",
