      "description": "By 1997, Mike Portnoy had made the full transition from the Tama Artstar II birch shells he used on *Awake* to the Tama Starclassic Maple series. The 10-ply maple construction represented Tama's flagship professional offering — denser and with more sustain than the earlier Artstar birch shells, and better suited to the melodic, mid-tempo material that Elektra was pushing Dream Theater to record.\n\nMaple shells resonate differently from birch. Where birch provides a focused, punchy attack with a relatively fast decay, maple offers a rounder, warmer tone with longer sustain. For an album like *Falling into Infinity* — where tracks like \"Hollow Years\" and \"New Millennium\" demanded drumming that supported melody rather than overpowering it — the maple shell character was ideally suited.\n\nThe double 22\"x18\" bass drum configuration carried over from the *Awake* era, but the deeper 18\" shell depth produced noticeably more low-end body than the 16\" configuration Portnoy had used previously. On \"Lines in the Sand\" and \"Trial of Tears,\" this extra bass drum mass gave the more ambitious prog passages additional foundation without adding visual complexity.\n\nThe six-tom setup from 8\" to 16\" gave Portnoy the full melodic fill range his compositional approach demanded. Even on shorter, more radio-accessible tracks, Portnoy's tom work maintained the narrative quality — fills functioning as melodic statements rather than filler. Tama's Star-Cast mounting allowed each drum to resonate freely, maximizing the warmth of the maple construction.",
