      "description": "For the *Nightmare* sessions, Mike Portnoy brought a Tama Starclassic Maple kit — the shell platform that had defined much of his mid-period career and remained in his arsenal for guest and touring contexts alongside the Starclassic Bubinga he used for Dream Theater's studio work.\n\nThe Starclassic Maple's character suited the *Nightmare* material well. Where bubinga delivers sharper attack and faster decay — ideal for the technical complexity of Dream Theater's *Systematic Chaos* — maple shells produce a warmer, more resonant fundamental tone that supports the emotional weight of A7X's arrangements. \"So Far Away,\" the album's Grammy-nominated tribute ballad to The Rev, required a kit that could hold space rather than cut through it. The maple shells' sustain and warmth delivered that.\n\nPortnoy's configuration was his established large-format touring setup: double 22\"x18\" bass drums, five rack toms (8\" through 14\"), and three floor toms (14\", 16\", 18\"). The Rev had been a drummer who used an expansive kit — multiple toms, complex cymbal arrangements — so Portnoy's large touring rig was well-suited to covering The Rev's original drum parts without compromise.\n\nTama's Star-Cast mounting system preserved the shells' resonance across the full configuration. Each drum spoke clearly, essential for the melodic tom figures The Rev had composed throughout the album's arrangements. The setup was designed for physical performance at high demand — exactly what the emotional intensity of recording a tribute album required.",
